subject: Define Redfish interface "/Registries/Bios" and enable Attributes property
commitMessage:
Define Redfish interface "/Registries/Bios" and enable Attributes property

1. Define Redfish interface "/Registries/Bios" for BIOS Attribute Registry
   RBC Daemon provide method to get BIOS attribute registry.
2. Enable Attributes property for BIOS resource
3. Define Redfish interface "/Systems/system/Bios/Settings" for BIOS
settings
4. RBC daemon is at
https://gerrit.openbmc-project.xyz/#/c/openbmc/bios-settings-mgr/+/35563/
5. IPMI command implementation is at
https://gerrit.openbmc-project.xyz/#/c/openbmc/intel-ipmi-oem/+/30827/
6. Property design is at
https://github.com/openbmc/phosphor-dbus-interfaces/tree/master/xyz/openbmc_project/BIOSConfig
7. Design doc is at
https://github.com/openbmc/docs/blob/master/designs/remote-bios-configuration.md
8. There will be 95 test cases for this feature in the validation team.

Tested:
1. Use postman could get all the attributes in bios
resouce, get bios settings, get bios attribute
registry.

Patch Set 24:

Kuiying,

Please take a look around the codebase and familiarize yourself with the COMMON_ERRORS.md document.  You've made a number of missteps that would've been easily caught with a little review on your part before you pushed this.  Overall, you need to think more about "how can this fail, and what is the behavior when it does" as you've skipped over lots of error handling.  Having a maintainer have to point out the fact that you don't check your pointers for null is a waste of everyone's time (including yours) and slows down getting your patch on master.

This is a registry, which means that it shouldn't be changing as the result of a dbus call, it should be fixed for a given system, which means it can simply be checked in as a static file, or multiple static files for the various configs we support, and should require calling no code (or possibly minimal code to select the right registry).

Considering this registry will be different between Intel, AMD, ARM and IBM systems, giving them them all the same name, namespace, and version seems like a problem when it comes to Redfish, as it is incorrect as two systems would report the same version and name for the attribute registry, but different available attributes.
